<br>
Da' Facts on Pets<br>
<br>
1. 99% of all problems caused by pets are DIRECTLY RELATED TO THE IGNORANCE OF THE MAGE not to pets in general.<br>
This includes but is not limited to;<br>
 A. Mages that do not know what /pet guard here is for, if you see a mage pet in a camp and it is doing anything other than standing in one spot, rotating to face the nearest enemy, then you have a dumbass Mage. Pets that are not put into guard or sit will roam, and when the mage moves to a spot in the area that has pathing issues, the pet can run off.<br>
 B. Mages that have not learned what summon companion is yet, If you have a mage that does not have it memorized in tight and or areas with bad pathing, you have a dumbass mage.<br>
 C. Mages that do not realize that they have a built in Memblur spell called /pet back off and /pet as you were. If the pet is on a mob, and the mage gets hit by another, the mage SHOULD immediately /pet back off and then reassist. If the mage fails to do so, then the pet will jump the mob that hit the mage immediately after the first is dead. If this happens, you have a dumbass mage. (One exception is sometimes, you want this chain to occur)<br>
 D. Mages that do not have a hotkey that has 6 lines of /pet back off are dumbasses, simply because a single line hit is not enough.<br>
 E. Mages that do not know how to work with enchanters because all they have ever done is solo are dumbasses, because a well timed spam of pet back off combined with an enchanter possessing a clue ( stun, dazzle etc) will prevent 99% of all pet incidents. <br>
 F. If you have 10 unmezzed mobs running around hitting everything, and the mage is sitting then you have a dumbass mage ( really this applies to all casters)<br>
<br>
2. The other 1% is because of 1 factor.<br>
 A. Poor enchanters only make it harder on mages. If you have the mob mezzed, and it breaks mez and starts casting on my pet, then the last thing a enchanter should be doing is screaming about the pet. They need to STFU and stun the mob, so the mage can get their pet off then remez it long term. If your mage is not paying attention, then you need to ask him to stop eating Fruit Loops and pay attention or find another group.<br>
<br>
Okay so you ask, what does this all mean?? Well let me tell you. Stripping pet classes of their pets (minus crazy enchanter pets that even they do not like) is like asking the clerics not to heal, the shamans not to buff, the wizards not to nuke, the warriors not to dual wield, etc. The only place pets should be banned is in the first 20 minutes of a Hate/Fear break type situation where things are so hectic that breathing is not permitted, but even then I question the logic unless the previously mentioned dumbass mage problem is occuring. <br>
<br>
Right now we do not allow mage pets on Trak attacks, do you realize that even the level 49 water pet can double and triple hit for 56 damage. Has a PR that no player can match, and is utterly expendable? Mages should be running up the path, then casting a water pet and sending it in. Anytime that you are dealing with a single mob situation there is no excuse for not sending pets at the mob.  <p>Kailere Drowsbane of Veeshan -Paladin of 55 summers<BR>
